The XRD patterns for the CKCDs and V-CKCDs have shown the sharp diffraction peaks. In comparison with the diffraction peaks of CKCDs, the distinct and intensely sharpened peaks at diffraction angles of 17.4°, 23.86°, 29.68°, 30.72°, 34°, 35.22°, 38.44°, 45.74°, and 46.48° were observed in V-CKCDs ( Fig. 2
A). These results are corroborating with the HRTEM results of CKCDs and V-CKCDs in signifying the well-crystallinity. The stability of the Hg2+-treated V-CKCDs was thoroughly studied by XRD technique. Significantly, no distinction in their peak positions was observed as shown in Fig. S6 . This shows that the crystallinity of V-CKCDs is not influenced by the presence of Hg2+, which suggests that V-CKCDs are reasonably stable. The TGA analysis of CKCDs and V-CKCDs was performed for understanding thermal stability. The total weight loss in the CKCDs was found to be approximately 78 %, which suggested that the CKCDs are not adequately stable at higher temperatures. However, the V-CKCDs have exhibited excellent thermal stability with the overall weight loss around 22.5 % as shown in Fig. 2 B. We believed that this response may have resulted from the aniline and vinyl groups present on the V-CKCDs. Raman spectroscopy studies were conducted for the CKCDs and V-CKCDs to investigate the crystallinity and the extent of functionalization in the V-CKCDs (
Fig. S7
). Raman spectra of CKCDs have shown two distinct peaks at 1372 and 1571 cm−1, which attributed to the D and G bands. Similarly, V-CKCDs have also exhibited a couple of bands at 1367 and 1533 cm−1. These bands are responsible for sp3 and sp2 carbons available in the both CKCDs and V-CKCDs. Furthermore, the ID/IG ratios were increased from 0.58 (for CKCDs) to 0.84 (for V-CKCDs) after the 4-VA functionalization. These results are corroborating with the covalent functionalization between CKCDs and V-CKCDs [40]. Moreover, the ID/IG ratio (<1) of CKCDs and V-CKCDs is clearly representing their high crystallinity, which is consistent with the XRD results [41]. Zeta potential measurements were carried out for the CKCDs and V-CKCDs against Hg2+ and Cys in the presence of PBS of pH 5.5 (
Fig. S8
). The zeta potential values for the CKCDs and V-CKCDs were found to be −14.16 and −11.73 mV, respectively. The obtained values are corresponding to their surface negative charges resulting from the (–OH) and (CO) functional groups over the CKCDs and V-CKCDs. The slight reduction in the zeta potential value of V-CKCDs (-11.73 mV) might be responsible for the moderate protonation of vinyl and amine moieties. Further, the V-CKCDs after adding Hg2+ (0.5 μM) have shown the zeta potential value of 0.35 mV and again, the V-CKCDs-Hg2+ has exhibited the zeta potential of 2.59 mV by adding Cys (4 μM). The shift towards the positive zeta potential was favored from the slightly acidic (pH 5.5) condition and also the obtained results are suggesting the colloidal stability of the prepared CKCDs and V-CKCDs.

The V-CKCDs were employed for detecting Hg2+ in real water samples by applying the standard addition method. Various Hg2+ concentrations (0.05, 0.1, 0.2, and 0.5 µM) were spiked with stream and tap water samples. The good recovery values were achieved with recovery percentages including 96.1–103.7 % and 95.8–105.6 %, respectively (

                           Table S1

                        ). The relative standard deviation (RSD) values for spike samples were found to be < 6.5 %, which signify the practicality of the developed fluorescence sensor (i.e., V-CKCDs) against the Hg2+ detection. These results are suggesting that the V-CKCDs are reliable sensing platform for Hg2+ sensing in the daily-basis real water samples. Again, V-CKCDs were used to detect Cys in spiked human serum samples at different concentrations (0.5, 2.5, 3.5, and 4.0 µM). The recovery values for these spiked samples were obtained as 95.1–100.7 % (

                           Table S2

                        ). The developed V-CKCDs can be adequately detect Cys in the human serum with a good sensing potential.
